        "excerpt": "All the sons of Israel from Dan to Beersheba… came out, and the congregation assembled as one man to the LORD at Mizpah.",
        "body": "The opening scene of Judges 20 depicts one of the most remarkable corporate assemblies in the Old Testament. The geographic formula 'from Dan to Beersheba' marks the north-south extent of the land — every tribe except Benjamin is represented, along with the Transjordanian territory of Gilead. Four hundred thousand foot soldiers, 'the assembly of the people of God' (20:2, qahal elohim), gather at Mizpah to hear testimony and deliberate verdict. The vocabulary is judicial and covenantal: this is not a war council but a covenant court.\n\nThe Levite's testimony (20:4-7) is controlled and strategic. He narrates the crime from his own vantage point, omitting his own role in sending his concubine to the door (19:25), but the assembly does not press for cross-examination. The narrator has already given the reader the fuller account in chapter 19; here the assembly hears a version sufficiently true to warrant action. The Levite invokes a category that recurs across Judges: 'lewd and disgraceful act in Israel' (zimmah and nevalah, 20:6). Both terms appear in Deuteronomy's covenant violation vocabulary and signal that what happened at Gibeah was not merely criminal but covenantally defiling — the kind of act that, left unpurged, corrupts the entire community (cf. Deut. 22:21; Josh. 7:15).\n\nThe assembly's response is total: 'Not one of us will go to his tent, nor will any of us return to his house' (20:8). Before the tribes turn to tactics (20:9-10), they make a vow of corporate commitment. This sequence matters — the moral resolve precedes the military plan. And before military action, Israel attempts the legally required step of Deuteronomy 13:14 — careful inquiry into the tribe of Benjamin, followed by a demand for the surrender of the guilty (20:12-13). Benjamin's refusal is what makes the subsequent war just, not merely inevitable.\n\nThe military statistics of verses 15-17 frame the human equation: 26,700 Benjaminites against 400,000 Israelites — a 15:1 disparity. The narrator mentions the 700 elite left-handed slingers of Gibeah (20:16) with a detail that functions as irony: this tribe that cannot recognize moral precision (refusing to purge obvious wickedness) has cultivated extraordinary physical precision (slingers who do not miss a hair's breadth). Skill deployed in defense of depravity is worse than no skill at all.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qahal elohim* (assembly of God's people, v.2) carries covenantal weight — the same term used for Israel's sacral assembly at Sinai (Deut. 9:10; 10:4). *Zimmah* (lewd act, v.6) and *nevalah* (disgraceful folly, vv.6, 10) are covenant-violation terms: nevalah in particular marks an act so disordering that it tears the fabric of covenantal community."
