        "body": "Israel's first consultation with God (20:18) is procedurally correct but spiritually thin. The question asked is narrow: who leads the advance? The LORD answers with Judah — the same tribe He appointed as the vanguard in the conquest itself (Judg. 1:1-2), and the tribe from which the Messianic line descends. The answer is valid. But the assembly has not asked the question that matters most: 'Will we succeed? Are we approaching this in a way that honors You?' The inquiry is tactical, not penitential.\n\nThe result is catastrophic. Twenty-two thousand Israelite soldiers — men who drew the sword (20:17) — fall on the first day. The text gives no divine explanation for the defeat. The narrator simply reports it, leaving the reader in the same bewilderment as the army. This is deliberate. The silence of verse 21 is theologically louder than any explanation would be: God does not always reward correct procedure with immediate vindication. The cause can be right while the heart's preparation is insufficient.\n\nVerse 22 records Israel's response: they 'encouraged themselves' (chazaq, strengthened themselves) and returned to their battle positions. Chazaq is a strong word — active, intentional self-fortification — and it is commendable as far as it goes. But the reader notices what is absent: there is no sacrifice, no fasting, no prostration. Israel weeps at Bethel until evening (20:23) and asks whether to continue — a genuine inquiry, but one that does not yet reach the depth the crisis demands. God still says 'Go up,' still without a promise of victory. The second day's defeat (18,000 men, 20:25) will force the issue.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaal* (to inquire, consult) in v.18 is the same verb used for legitimate priestly consultation throughout the OT (cf. Num. 27:21; Judg. 1:1). The verb does not guarantee the spirit of the inquiry — only its form. *Chazaq* (strengthened, v.22) is used of both holy fortitude (Josh. 1:6) and stubborn resistance (Exod. 7:13); the context here suggests genuine courage that has not yet been purified by penitence."
