        "body": "The third day's battle is narrated with the most tactical detail in the chapter, and the detail is intentional. Israel now has a divine promise (20:28) and a military plan (the ambush, 20:29) — both of which are necessary. The strategy echoes Joshua 8:2-21 with near-identical elements: feigned retreat, ambush force hidden nearby, signal fire, encirclement. The Joshua 8 parallel is not coincidental. The narrator is telling the reader that Israel is finally fighting as a people who remember how God operates — through covenant promise and tactical obedience, not through numerical superiority or moral indignation alone.\n\nThe Benjaminites are drawn out from Gibeah by the apparent retreat (20:31-32), read the early casualties as confirmation of their previous victories ('Surely they are defeated before us as in the first battle,' 20:32), and advance confidently into the ambush. The narrator pauses to note the fatal irony: 'Benjamin did not know that disaster was close to them' (20:34). The Hebrew word for disaster is ra — the same term used for the original wickedness at Gibeah (20:3, 12, 13). The evil they refused to purge now returns as the evil that overtakes them.\n\nThe signal fire (20:38-40) — a column of smoke rising from the city — is the chapter's most arresting image. Gibeah, the city that Benjamin chose to defend rather than discipline, becomes the visual proof of Benjamin's defeat. When the Benjaminites turn and see their own city burning, the narrative frame collapses: they are now refugees fleeing toward the wilderness, the battle reversed in a moment. Verse 35 names the agent: 'The LORD struck Benjamin before Israel.' The entire thirty-verse battle account has been leading to this one sentence. Human strategy was real and necessary, but it was instrumental, not causal. The LORD is the decisive actor.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nagaph* (struck, defeated, v.35) — the verb of divine judgment most commonly used when the LORD acts against Israel's enemies in holy war (cf. Num. 14:42; Josh. 10:10). Its use here with YHWH as explicit subject is the narrator's theological flag: this victory belongs to the covenant God, not to the coalition."
