        "number": 5,
        "title": "Near-annihilation and the remnant of 600 — judgment within covenant mercy",
        "range": "20:36-48",
        "excerpt": "But 600 men turned and fled toward the wilderness to the rock of Rimmon, and they remained at the rock of Rimmon four months.",
        "body": "The final section narrates the complete collapse of Benjamin's military resistance and the near-extinction of the tribe. The narrative doubles back in verses 36-41 to retell the battle's final phase from Benjamin's perspective — a Hebrew narrative technique that foregrounds the subjective experience of the defeated before returning to the comprehensive casualty count. The technique is pastorally significant: the narrator does not permit the reader to simply exult in the victory. We watch the Benjaminites realize, in real time, that disaster has arrived.\n\nThe casualty count is staggering: 18,000 fall in the immediate rout (20:44), 5,000 more on the roads, 2,000 at Gidom — 25,000 swordsmen in total (20:46). The number represents nearly the entire fighting force of the tribe (26,700 had initially mustered, 20:15). Israel then extends the judgment to the non-combatant population and the cities themselves (20:48), executing what Deuteronomy 13:15-16 required for a city that had harbored covenant apostasy: the edge of the sword, the cattle, the burning of the city. The herem (ban, total destruction) vocabulary is present without the word itself — the actions describe it.\n\nYet the narrator is careful: '600 men turned and fled toward the wilderness to the rock of Rimmon' (20:47). The number is not left to chance. The LORD who authorized the war did not authorize extinction. Six hundred men — enough to constitute a remnant, not enough to constitute a tribe — are preserved. The four-month period at Rimmon creates the crisis of chapter 21 (how does a surviving remnant of 600 bachelors continue a tribe?) but also creates the space for chapter 21's solution. Covenant judgment in the Old Testament is severe but not absolute when the covenant people remain within its frame. The remnant theology operative here — devastation that preserves a seed — is the same theology Isaiah will later apply to all Israel under Assyrian judgment (Isa. 10:20-22; cf. Rom. 9:27-29). Benjamin's 600 are the forerunners of every biblical remnant.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sela Rimmon* (rock of Rimmon, vv.45, 47) — a natural limestone fortress in the wilderness east of Gibeah; the rock's inaccessibility explains why Israel did not pursue the 600 further. The verb *radaph* (pursued, v.43) with *menuchah* (without rest) captures the relentlessness of the final rout. *Chayil* (valor, vv.44, 46) — the word used throughout the OT for military excellence and covenant faithfulness (cf. Ruth 3:11; Prov. 31:10); the narrator grants Benjamin's soldiers their dignity even in defeat."
